This end cap "appeared" when I was test-printing reduced-size models for my V-slot tap guide, (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2105706). I refined the design a bit to make a friction-fit end cap. I was going to need some anyway for my D-bot build.

These require a pretty "tight" printer in order to print a part that fits. You must deburr cut extrusions before these will fit. You should be doing that anyway, right?

When installing, it will feel like it won't fit and then it does. When installing 2 in the 20x40 extrusions, you may have to tap on it a little or lightly sand the adjoining edges, though I haven't had to do that with any of the models in the photos.

I've discovered that these fit well and tightly the first few times they're used but, as expected, multiple insertions and removals make for a loose fit. A drop of glue in one corner should easily hold the entire cap securely in the extrusion and still be removable, if needed.

I've included two versions. One has a 5mm hole to allow access to the extrusion's center.

description.text:
Le savon à la glycérine à l’avantage d’être très facile et rapide à réaliser. On peut en plus y insérer de petits objets pour le personnaliser. J’ai réalisé quelques impressions simples avec graphismes inspirés de l’univers d’Harry Potter ainsi que le nom de chaque invité. Pour donner au savon un aspect magique, j’y ai également mis une araignée phosphorescente. Elle est invisible à la lumière, mais bien visible dans le noir. De quoi effrayer les ami(e)s lorsqu’ils (elles) rentrent dans la salle de bain !!!!

Informations :

Temps d’impression 3D* : 3min
Temps de réalisation : 30min
Niveau de difficulté : Débutant

More details on : www.buse-toi-meme.com

Le Matériel : (pour 1 savon)

0,05m de PLA Noir, du nGen (ce filament a un aspect +brillant que le PLA) ou du PLA souple ( ça a l’avantage de faire moins mal aux mains lorsque l’on utilisera le savon!)
500g de Melt&Pour transparent pour 1 moule de 6 savons environ
1 araignée phosphorescente
1 moule silicone
1 récipient en verre compatible micro-onde
Poudre cosmétique Or (facultatif)
Quelques gouttes d’huiles essentielles
Film alimentaire
Alcool dans un contenant en spray

La Réalisation :

1.Télécharger le fichier .stl avec les graphismes inspirés de l’univers d’Harry Potter sur votre ordinateur : busetoimeme-impression3d-HarryPotter-Savon.
2.Vous pouvez réaliser un fichier .stl avec les prénoms des invités. C’est une modélisation simple : Ecrivez les prénoms des invités dans votre logiciel 3D, puis extrudez les lignes obtenues. Enregistrez en .stl. Attention à respecter 2 critères : l’épaisseur des lettres doit être au minimum de 0,5 mm et l’extrusion doit faire au moins 0,5mm.

2.Ouvrir le(s) fichier(s) dans votre logiciel d’impression (Cura, CraftWare…).
3.Réglez les paramètres spécifiques suivants ou choisissez le mode qualité standard prédéfini par votre logiciel:

Vitesse d’impression : 50 mm/s
Type de support : Aucun
Type d’accroche sur le plateau : Aucun

4.Enregistrez votre Gcode

Préparation de la machine :

1.Insérez le filament choisi
2.Vérifiez les attributs de l’imprimante comme suit :

PLA : T° buse : 210°C – T° plateau : 60°C
nGen : T° buse : 220°C – T° plateau : 75°C

3.Mettez une fine couche de colle sur le plateau (colle papier blanche en bâton – pas la peine d’avoir de la colle spéciale – Un plateau propre avec une fine couche de colle posée de façon uniforme permet d’avoir un meilleur état de surface au final.)
4.Chargez le fichier GCode dans l’imprimante et lancez l’impression.
5.Récupérez les objets à la fin de l’impression.

Mise en œuvre :

1.Préparer les ingrédients
2.Couper le pain de Melt and Pour en cubes de 2 cm de côté environ
3.Faire fondre au micro-onde. La totalité des cubes doit être fondu (environ 30 secondes/100 gr – allez-y doucement pour ne pas bruler la base)
4.Pendant ce temps, vaporiser les moules avec de l’alcool en spray pour éviter les bulles
5.Mettre un peu de poudre dorée au fond de chaque moule puis poser l’araignée sur le dos
6.Ajouter quelques gouttes d’huiles essentielles dans le Melt&Pour et mélanger
7.Verser dans les moules jusqu’à moitié.
8.Aspergez chaque impression d’un peu d’alcool et les mettre dans le savon. Pensez à les mettre à l’envers pour que la lecture se fasse dans le bon sens une fois démoulé.
9.Aspergez la surface du savon et remplissez jusqu’en haut du moule.
10.Laissez refroidir et placez 10 min au congélateur.
11.Démoulez et emballez les savons dans du film alimentaire

Ce jeu est inspiré de différents tutos glanés sur le net et du célèbre Beer Pong. Ici, pas d’alcool, mais des bonbons aux goûts surprenants pour ne pas dire répugnants.

Règle du jeu :

On joue 1 contre 1.

Comme pour le jeu d’origine, deux rangs de gobelets sont opposés face à face, sur les côtés opposés d’une table, entre les deux rangées de gobelets sont disposés des mini-cercles inspirés du jeu de Quidditch. Les deux joueurs s’affrontant doivent alors faire atterrir une balle dans l’un des 10 verres de leur adversaire en passant par un des cercles. Si le lanceur atteint son but, le joueur perdant doit prendre un bonbon « JELLY BELLY BEAN ». Le joueur perdant est remplacé par un autre camarade et ainsi de suite.

Informations :

Temps d’impression 3D* : 3×45 min
Temps de réalisation : 30min
Niveau de difficulté : Débutant

More details : www.buse-toi-meme.com

Le Matériel :

3x 0,5m de PLA
1 Bombe de peinture Or
3 bouteilles en verre 33cl
20 gobelets en plastiques
3 pic brochettes en bois
1 ou 2 boite(s) de « Jelly Belly Beans » Harry Potter (se trouvent facilement sur le net)
1 balle de Ping Pong ou en polystyrène (attention il faut de la peinture en bombe acrylique pour le polystyrène – par contre la peinture acrylique ne sera pas assez couvrante pour les bouteilles)
De la pâte à modeler
De quoi lester les bouteilles et les gobelets (sable, sucre, pâte à modeler, petits cailloux..)
Colle cyanoacrylate type Loctite Gel

La Réalisation :

Préparation du Fichier :

1.Télécharger le fichier .stl sur votre ordinateur : busetoimeme-impression3d-HarryPotter-Quidditch.
2.Ouvrir le fichier dans votre logiciel d’impression (Cura, CraftWare…).
3.Réglez les paramètres spécifiques suivants ou choisissez le mode qualité standard prédéfini par votre logiciel:

Vitesse d’impression : 50 mm/s
Type de support : Aucun
Type d’accroche sur le plateau : Aucun

4.Enregistrez votre Gcode.

Préparation de la machine :

1.Insérez le filament PLA si besoin
2.Vérifiez les attributs de l’imprimante comme suit :

T° buse : 210°C
T° plateau : 60°C

3.Mettez une fine couche de colle sur le plateau (colle papier blanche en bâton – pas la peine d’avoir de la colle spéciale – Un plateau propre avec une fine couche de colle posée de façon uniforme permet d’avoir un meilleur état de surface au final.)
4.Chargez le fichier GCode dans l’imprimante et lancez l’impression.
5.Récupérez les objets à la fin de l’impression
6.Renouveler les opérations 3 fois pour avoir 3 cercles.

Mise en œuvre :
1.Lestez les bouteilles avec du sable puis bouchez le goulot avec un peu de pâte à modeler.
2.Coller avec un peu de cyanoacrylate le cercle avec le petit embout et laissez prendre la colle.
3.Coller le pic brochette en bois dans l’embout et laisser prendre la colle.
4.Piquez les anneaux dans la pâte à modeler des bouteilles. Un anneau doit être plus haut que les autres. Pour cela vous pouvez raccourcir un pic à brochette avant de le piquer dans la pâte à modeler.
5.Peindre à la bombe de peinture les bouteilles et la balle.

Mise en place :
1.Sur une table disposez à chaque extrémité les gobelets de façon à former un triangle
2.Lestez chaque gobelet
3.Disposez en ligne et au centre de la table les 3 bouteilles avec l’anneau le plus haut au centre.

title: Micro-Rover for the Raspberry Pi Zero

description.text:
Micro-Rover for Raspberry Pi Zero

A 3D printable chassis that uses a Raspberry Pi Zero and two 2-channel motor-drivers with aux outputs to drive four separate motors with each motor separately steered with a micro-servo.

Use the Raspberry Pi to steer the wheels and control the motor speeds to the execute turns and manoeuvres that can only be equalled using mecanum wheels.

The complete chassis is made up from two copies of the sub-chassis assembly, joined together with Lego Technic beams. And since it's compatible with Lego Technic partrs, it can be integrated into more complex designs using Lego Technic components.

Note 1: This was actually printed on a WanHao 5DS Mini using PLA, printed with a layer thickness of 0.1mm.

The Tyres need to be printed using NinjaFlex or similar material. I wasn't able to print these on the Wanhao 5DS Mini due to the type of extruder, so please check that you're able to print Ninjaflex or have access to someone who can, before trying to re-create this Thing.

Assembly Instructions

Assembly is relatively easy after printing, with just a few readily available nuts & bolts.

To assemble the full Micro-Rover demonstrated in this project, you'll need:

For the controller:
1 x Raspberry Pi Zero plus WiFi or Raspberry Pi Zero W;
2 x PiZ-Moto 2-channel motor controller or any similar motor controller(s) that supports a total of four small motors;

For the rover assembly:
4 x 6v 50:1 micro geared motors;
4 x Tower-Pro SG9 micro servos;
1 x 4-cell AA battery holder; (Note that the longer 2 x 4 cell design works better here as it conveniently just hangs under the chassis);
4 x AA batteries;
4 x M1.6 x 6mm slotted cheese-head screw
(Just 1 is used to secure each micro-geared motor into the motor assembly)
4 x M3 x 20 pan-head machine screw
(for attaching the SubChassisTop to SubChassisBase);
4 x M2.5 x 8mm pan-head machine screw
(used as the bottom pivot for the motor assembly);
4 x M2.5 full-nut
(Used to secure the bottom pivot for the motor assembly)
4 2.5mm x 6mm x 3mm (id x od x h) bearing
(used as the bottom pivot for the motor assembly);

The battery pack just hangs under the chassis using tie-wraps. I recommend using 3mm wide x 150mm long tie wraps. But don't tighten too much, just enough to hold it in place but loose enough to be able to pull the battery pack out to replace the batteries.

To assemble the wheels:
4 x M2 x 6mm pan-head machine screw
(Used to secure the wheel onto the motor shaft);
4 x M2 full nut
(Inserted into wheel hub to provide a thread for the M2 screw that secures the wheel onto the motor shaft);

To assemble the Raspberry Pi onto the chassis:
4 x M2.5 x 5mm pan-head screws
4 x M2.5 full-nut
(optional) 4 x M2.5mm x 12mm M-F pillar to raise the Raspberry Pi off the chassis. This is needed if you're using a WiFi dongle plugged into the side of the Raspberry Pi. If you don't use this then the external WiFi dongle will interfere with the steering.

The Python code used to test this is available in the examples folder of the package for the PiZ-Moto motor-controller on GitHub:

https://github.com/astro-designs/piz-moto

It is designed for metric, but the shape is the same for UTS, so you can use the library, specifying the thread pitch you need, to make UTS.

I've added the OpenSCAD - written to work as a library allowing nut, bolt, or arbitrary sections of thread - have fun.

Note: 8th March, corrected dimensions!

P.S. I have looked through a load of the other thread libraries on here - I think I am the only one that has constructed it in this way - some interesting different approaches to the same problem though. Fun.

Simply print vertically (no support needed), then solder two thin spade connectors (without insulation) to an MR16 light bulb and bend them outwards to fit in the slots in the BL1013 battery (see picture). Poke the MR16 in the hole, check it works, then glue it in.

The LED bulb used in the pictures is an MR11, but MR16s work too and produce signficantly more light. Most good LED light bulbs contain a switching power supply which means they run off 10.8v at exactly the same brightness that they do off 12v.

title: Terminal cover for 12V 360W 30A LED PSU with Switched Mains Inlet

description.text:
Having bought a 30A power supply for my Makerfarm Prusa i3, I was concerned that the terminals were all too readily accessible.  
I decided to make this cover to provide a good degree of protection for the live terminals while adding a DP switched inlet for the mains.  
The PSU in question measures 215mm x 115mm x 50mm. The terminals sit on a 'plinth' along the lower front edge. If you've got one, you'll know what I mean.  
This is my first design and bespoke 3D print, so I was relieved that it worked as well as it did. Enjoy!

I printed this in ABS. Warping was a real issue, even with mouse ears, but it's functional. I think I'm getting to grips with the warping issue, now, so a reprint may be in order.  
I redrilled the side mounting holes with an M2.5 drill bit, which allowed me to screw M3 cap head screws straight in. These fix through the existing slots on the metal frame of the PSU.  
The cable exit holes along the front needed the merest touch with a reamer to get the perfect size for Maplin 50-025mm cable. Of course, you can resize to suit your chosen cable. I'd recommend adding tie wraps where the cables exit the cover to act as a crude strain relief. That said, I didn't.  
I soldered the connections to the DP switch and IEC mains inlet.

description.text: I designed this rocket and fin collar for a great air rocket launcher I got from the Maker Shed (http://www.makershed.com/products/compressed-air-rocket-launcher-v22). I wanted my second grade students to be able to see the rocket in flight without fins, and then to be able to design and easily attach their own cardboard fins for testing. The rocket has a small ridge and fits in a groove on the inside of the collar to prevent spinning during flight. The air rocket is quite powerful, so we wear eye protection, and the kids stand well back. The difference in flight is obvious, and the students enjoyed the whole experience very much.

Cleanup

The inner rim of the rocket body and the collar both need a couple of shaving passes with an exacto knife and should then fit perfectly.
<iframe allowfullscreen="None" frameborder="0" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/4u1pyOSnjtk" ></iframe>

Notes

The rocket file here has no text on it, and the collar does not have the notch for the text.

The collars stay on the rocket body during flight and return, but the little arms that secure the fins can sometimes break if it lands wrong. I'd suggest printing several collars.

The fins stay put during launch if they have 1/2 to 3/4 of an inch of cardboard sticking out of the tail end (as opposed to the fin end).

The launcher requires assembly, so allow time for that (have older students do it?).

The launcher valve can be tricky. I found this tip from Air Rocket Works very helpful:

"If the Quick Exhaust Valve Leaks: Sometimes, when using a bike pump, the QEV diaphragm will fail to seal the outlet, and the air will leak out the launch tube with each pump. There is one super-easy trick that almost always works if the QEV diaphragm fails to seal. First, with the slide valve in the "Launch" position, complete one stroke on the bike pump. This will build up pressure in the hose of the bike pump. Next, slide the valve to the "Pressurize" position. The sudden inrush of pressure built up in the pump hose will almost always seat the QEV diaphragm. In fact, the more you launch, the more the diaphragm gets broken in. Now, pump up the chamber normally."

I recently got into the hobby of silk screening. So I designed this holder/rack to mount onto a wall. You can snap the silk screen into the holder and it will support it so it can dry or for storage to keep it off of your workspace.
This was designed to fit a silk screen from www.silkscreeningsupplies.com so adjustments may need to be made for it to fit other screens. The fit is tight, requiring a small amount of pressure to snap the screen in place as well as to remove it.
This came out very sturdy with the angled supports.

1] Print one per screen for small screens; maybe two per screen for large screens (or if you prefer more support). I used 25% infill every two layers.
2] Mount to your wall or stud using adequate screws and washers. I use washers to spread out the pressure from the screw so the plastic does not get crushed.

This is a mounting system that I use for 9 gram sized servos.
For large foam aircraft I glue the box in place then mount the servo mount to it using 4 * 3mm screws, placing a small piece of foam between the servo & the box to secure the servo.
For smaller foamies I use hot glue to glue the servo to the mount plate & then the mount plate to the foam.
For balsa planes I use hot glue to glue the servo to the mount plate then screw the plate to the plane.
The cover can be used in all configurations.

These will print best at 100% infill, 3 perimeters, 3 top & bottom layers & with supports (no supports needed for just the mount plates). These settings seem to work well with a .35mm tip on my prusa I3 with PLA or ABS.
I have included my original 123D Design files for use if modifications are needed.

description.text:
Update June 01.:
Added a new version with and without an XT60 mount on the back and one without.
Gives better esc protection.
Infill 60% works for me the best.
Supports advised. Don't need a lot.

I changed the rear a tiny bit. The antenna mount is moved 4mm further to the rear and made it more vertical. Also raised the rear 5mm.
That will give a bit more space but the space inside is still less than the old one.

Also one thing. By the arms I added one bottom part. As you use a 4 in 1 esc. you can leave it there and mount the arms over the wires.
As you use an esc on the arm, remove the inner one or cut it open.

Latest update.

  • Stretched is finished.
    -30deg HD mount version is added to this X210 new.

Working on.

  • New version.
  • X210 pro version is in the making.

Please give feedback!!!

New version!
After some comments I made some changes.

The changes:

  • The esc protectors are now 1mm thick and 2.5mm raised. This gives the bigger esc's more space.
  • Added an extra zip tie hole on the inner side.
  • Front length changed. The length of the mid of the cam mounting hole till the front of the opening is no 28.25mm.
  • Side of the fpv cam the ridge that sits there is made a bit bigger to make it e bit more stiff.
  • front by the bottom plate now follows the line better. It is not only optical it also makes it a bit stronger.
  • VTX antenna mount moved 8mm to the front and angle is 10 degree more up. This is don so the short antenna's wil not hit the props.

Please let me now if the updates improved it and if there are other things.
The more feedback I get, the faster I can finish the pod and improve it.

Holes are still not there and can be made by using a sharp knife or soldering iron.
I did not ad them because I still work on the pod. As everything is ok I will ad them with also the step files so you can ad your own openings.

I hope to ad a cam mount version later tonight. This will be a 30 degree cam mount.
Other versions will follow.

The version with the lock nuts is not there yet. I changed this version and as this is ready, the other version will come back.

Other news for the X210 pro users.
I am working on a x210 pro version. It will get it's own thingverse number but I want to let you now that I am working on it.

Stretched X version will follow as both pods are ready.
I will design a bottom plate that will fit the pod and follows the flow. I make my own bottom plate so I can make it better fit and decide where I want the mounting holes.

Follow me on instagram as you want to now what is comming.
https://www.instagram.com/emiel1976/

This is a slight modification of @beardofzeus Pi Day Trophy! I wanted the Pi and the base to be in two different colors so I split his model in to two and added a tab and slot to connect the two.

The tab and slot are very tight and I used a lot of downward force to get the two to go together. I was okay with this because I want them to stay together.
